Amend the European Stability Pact
The European Stability Pact, which underpins the euro by putting in place constraints determining the size of budget deficits of member states of the Union, is in danger.
Germany, the heavyweight of the Union, has failed to meet its budget commitments to its European partners.
Furthermore, it has used its political weight to cover up the early warning signal of its deficit, set up by the European Commission in accordance with the terms of the European Stability Pact.
Today it's France who plays the bad guys.
The second in the Union, who was not very enthusiastic, is now officially declaring that it cannot meet its commitment to reduce the budget deficit, a year after the small Ireland received an official warning about its fiscal policies, despite budget surpluses and in a very severe manner.
Thus, four years after its signature, the stability pact is a real disaster.
Indeed, Europe seems very affected by the discussions aiming to eliminate it, as well as the discussions aiming to amend it.
And rightly so: the pact is poorly designed and its implementation was poorly done.
The limitation of the deficit to 3% of the GDP is arbitrary and does not take into account the fact that deficits automatically increase when the economy slows down.
Admitting this fact, the architects of the pact have worsened the situation by adopting two "ill-conceived" solutions.
They introduced a clause of safety that allowed any country to suspend its deficit limits in case of significant recession, but they defined it in such a way that any suspension is quasi-impossible in practice.
Concerned by the fact that serious slowdowns may undermine the ceiling on deficits, they decreed that a normal deficit was equivalent to no deficit at all.
Thus, each year, each country must submit a budget of projection for the next two years demonstrating how budget balance will be achieved at the right time.
The German commitment for 2002 was made in 2001, when its economy was developing at a reasonable pace.
The unexpected slowdown prevents Germany from achieving its goals.
The finance minister, Hans Eichel, decided, reasonably, not to worsen the situation by adopting a contractionary fiscal policy.
The Commission, seeking to project itself as the protector of the pact, wanted to issue a warning, but this decision had to be taken by real politicians, the Council of Finance Ministers.
No one wanted to embarrass Germany since everyone recognized that they could face the same problem in the future.
Thus, no warning was issued.
The situation of France is different.
In a period of election, politicians inevitably make promises, particularly on the reduction of the fiscal burden.
In a country where the fiscal burden is important, it's not just a question of showing good politics, it's also a question of showing good economics, as long as the budgetary expenses are also reduced.
However, France is also a country where everyone benefits from certain financial privileges funded by the state, and as a result, the budget cuts are definitely poorly perceived.
Thus, France cannot keep its objectives and the Commission has expressed its annoyance.
But France has mastered the art of defying the Union's laws.
Political maneuvers will follow, inevitably.
Economists and cynics are hardly surprised.
The pact's objective, to put in place a fiscal discipline among countries sharing the same currency, is quite acceptable.
However, the loss of control of their national monetary policy, the Union's members benefit from only one macroeconomic tool: fiscal policies.
The challenge is therefore to combine long-term discipline with short-term flexibility.
Just like promising to go on a diet before a big party, this challenge is not easy to reconcile.
The Stability Pact is too rudimentary and technocratic: the 3% target set by the Brussels bureaucrats cannot tie politicians to it.
The solution must be found elsewhere.
Fortunately, we don't have to look too far.
Monetary policy is also facing the same challenge.
It must stabilize prices in the long term while remaining sufficiently flexible in the short term to manage economic cycles.
Over the past ten years, monetary policy has achieved real success.
The recipe is the same everywhere: it just needs to delegate this policy to a competent group, the Central Bank, granting it the necessary political independence, and a clear and well-defined mandate.
Knowing that any misstep will have to be settled in the future, it's up to it to show good sense.
This has proven to be one of the major improvements in monetary policy of recent years.
The same approach should work for fiscal policy.
Surely some fear losing in democracy.
It is essential to understand that fiscal policy achieves two very different goals.
The first is structural and redistributive and concerns the importance of the budget and its detailed structure, both in terms of spending and in terms of revenue.
The decisions concerning these questions cannot be delegated and must remain in the hands of elected governments and be subject to parliamentary approval and management.
The second is macroeconomic: it is a question of defining the budget balance to manage fluctuations in cycles.
It differs little from monetary policy and can be delegated to an independent body.
Thus, the task of Europe is clear.
Each country must regain total control of its fiscal policies but delegate its macroeconomic components, its decisions on deficits or surpluses, to an independent Fiscal Policy Committee whose long-term objective is the stabilization (or reduction, for some countries) of public debt.
To ensure the result, the status of such a Committee and its mandates must be the subject of a consensus within the Union, without any interference from Brussels, without any arbitrary regulation, without any political decision-making, but simply relying on good common sense.
